english:
  title: Written on the Road to Liaoyang, Sent to Uiok Yi-mok and Hwang Eon-pyeong, My Contemporaries
  author: Shin Jong-ho
  language: eng
  text: |-
    At the river's head I watched you depart, the banner halting in the distance.
    Since our parting, sorrow lingers still, stretching long and deep.
    A thousand leagues of mountain passes fade as the year grows dim,
    And at the fifth watch, wind and snow startle my dreaming soul.

    Mountains chain toward the Huanglong fortress beyond the northern wastes,
    While the road leads onward to the Iron Phoenix city of Liaodong.
    Counting on my fingers, homecoming falls in mid-spring,
    And I imagine sharing a cup of wine with you then.
  footnotes:
    - The fifth watch refers to the early morning hours (around 3-5 AM in traditional timekeeping), evoking the speaker's restless, sleepless nights during travel.
    - The Huanglong fortress and Iron Phoenix city are poetic names for frontier fortifications in the Liaodong region, emphasizing the remote, barren landscape of the journey.
    - Mid-spring of the following year marks the anticipated reunion, suggesting the speaker expects to return within a year's time.
